<TEXT>
thousands of workers on thursday 
joined a 4dayold strike organized by prosandinista labor unions 
disrupting banking postal and telephone services nationwide 
police made no effort to dislodge strikers from government 
buildings and there was no indication that negotiations between 
the government and strikers would take place 
the usbacked government of president violeta barrios de 
chamorro has declared the strikes illegal saying they are 
politically motivated the government accuses the sandinistas of 
fomenting the labor unrest to undermine mrs chamorros economic 
recovery program 
on wednesday night seven prosandinista strike leaders were 
detained for two hours including lucio jimenez the 
secretarygeneral of the sandinista workers central the 
government said it was meant as a warning to other labor leaders to 
obey the law and not cause disorder 
the sandinistas say they are supporting the strikes because the 
new governments policies are threatening the gains of their 
revolution they contend the government has broken its promises not 
to fire public employees and say the unions are entitled under the 
constitution to a say in making national economic policy 
public employees won a 100 percent salary increase and other 
concessions during a crippling sandinistaled strike in may 
despite the governments warning the work stoppages continued 
to spread 
about 3800 telephone and postal workers joined the strike 
wednesday night operatorassisted international calls were not 
going through which caused considerable difficulties because most 
nicaraguans do not have directdial capability telex service 
continued normally 
the telephone and postal workers were staging what their leaders 
called a crossed arms strike similar to a sitin 
on thursday about 12500 bank employees began a similar strike 
action banks were open but no service was available 
about 3500 employees at the ministry of agriculture also went 
on strike thursday union leader jose angel bermudez said 
radio nicaragua reported wednesday night that thousands of farm 
workers had also gone on strike 
ramiro guardian vicepresident of the council of private 
enterprise a major business group said the strikes were 
preventing the planting of cotton an essential crop in nicaragua 
he blamed the labor protests on hotheaded sandinistas 
strikes continued thursday at other government offices 
including the customs service and the foreign labor construction 
transportation commerce and finance ministries 
air traffic controllers at sandino international airport 
threatened to strike and electrical workers announced they may 
begin scaled cuts of energy to the country 
students at most universities were also on strike on wednesday 
students briefly took over the stateowned radio nicaragua and 
national television system to read statements in favor of the 
strike 
jimenez claimed some 80000 workers in both the public and 
private sector were on strike as of thursday but estimates of the 
number of strikers by the sandinistaled unions have been 
exaggerated since the strike began on monday 
ariel bucardo president of the farmworkers federation said 
1000 members of his group were en route to managua the capital 
to support the strikers he said his union wanted the government to 
repeal laws allowing the return of some land confiscated by the 
sandinistas to the original owners 
the sandinistas redistributed some 5 million acres of land most 
of it held in absentia by wealthy nicaraguans who fled abroad 
during the sandinistas 10 years in power 
mrs chamorros new economic plans include returning most 
stateowned companies to the private sector and reorganizing the 
government both moves likely to cause job reductions 
the sandinistas led by daniel ortega were defeated in the feb 
25 elections by mrs chamorros 14party coalition 
</TEXT>
