<TEXT>
potentially fatal clots that develop after 
surgery may be triggered by high levels of a blood protein 
suggests a study published today 
mice that carried a human gene to make them produce excessive 
levels of the protein developed clots in their tails and hind feet 
researchers reported 
if further research confirms the link patients at risk for 
clotting may be identifiable before surgery by measuring their 
levels of the protein said researcher laurence erickson of the 
upjohn co in kalamazoo mich 
atrisk patients could receive preventive therapy and 
researchers may someday find a way to lower a persons level of the 
protein as a preventive step he said 
the protein called plasminogen activator inhibitor1 or pai1 
normally keeps the body from destroying clots prematurely 
the clotting condition is called deep venous thrombosis clots 
appear in veins usually in the leg they can kill if they break 
free and travel to the heart or lung 
clotting can appear after major surgery in cancer patients and 
people with an inherited tendency to develop them the condition is 
treated with anticlotting drugs 
between 200000 and 300000 cases occur in the united states 
each year with perhaps 20000 or more deaths a year said venous 
thrombosis researcher dr philip comp of the university of oklahoma 
comp said he believed it would be difficult to manipulate pai1 
levels to prevent the clotting disorder as for indicating patients 
at risk he said high levels in the blood may signal conditions 
unrelated to the risk even if high levels were related he said 
only a small percentage of people deemed at risk would probably get 
clots anyway 
erickson and upjohn colleagues presented their study findings in 
todays issue of the british journal nature 
the mice were given the extra pai1 gene before birth clotting 
appeared shortly after birth and resolved after production of 
pai1 fell back to normal 
</TEXT>
