maurice girodias who battled with censors while 
publishing lolita candy and other erotic best sellers 
died tuesday of a heart attack he suffered while giving a radio 
interview he was 71 
associates said he was stricken during an interview at jewish 
community radio studios in paris 
girodias the founder of olympia press in 1953 published first 
editions of works by henry miller lawrence durrell samuel 
beckett vladimir nabokov william burroughs jp donleavy nikos 
kazantzakis and jean genet among many others 
accused of promoting pornography girodias had numerous 
confrontations with french censors in the 1950s and 60s spent 
several days in prison and eventually was banned from publishing 
any further books in france he lived in exile in the united states 
from 1964 to 1974 when he was expelled in connection with a 
political novel which had former secretary of state henry kissinger 
as a main character 
