<TEXT>
after the floodwaters drained away 
shahar banu and her grandson returned to their village and found 
the earth slipping under their feet 
megaiyas land is eroding fast as it does every year the 
latest deluge by the monsoonswollen jamuna river and the receding 
water ate more loose topsoil this summer but now the erosion is 
threatening the village itself 
the countdown to destruction has started said hedayetullah 
almahmud a civil administrator at megaiya in the northern 
sirajganj district 
this summers flood washed away thousands of huts and weakened 
the foundations of the few concrete buildings in the village of 
3000 people 
district officials fear that in five years the erosion will 
trigger the collapse of the regions oldest establishment a school 
built in 1919 as well as a college a hospital a granary and at 
least 50 shops 
annual flooding is a major problem in bangladesh a lowlying 
delta crisscrossed by hundreds of rivers tens of thousands of tons 
of rice the staple of bangladeshis are lost to the encroaching 
rivers every year and the government reports hundreds of deaths 
the country is one of the poorest in the world with a per 
capita income of 160 when there are no floods bangladeshs 110 
million people are often reeling under drought the coastal areas 
are buffeted by frequent hurricanes 
flooding is a problem which brings temporary sufferings but 
here in our area river erosion is the main problem said abul 
kalaam azad a local official in megaiya 
mrs banu and her 15yearold grandson are resigned to the fate 
only allah can help us we have nothing else said mrs 
banu a 55yearold widow 
besides megaiya erosion is threatening the neighboring kazipur 
area also in sirajganj district azad said 
sirajganj 60 miles northwest of the capital dhaka was the 
worsthit in last months floods 
more than 600000 people were stranded in the sirajganj district 
and another 200000 in neighboring bogra people fled their 
inundated homes to take refuge atop levees and on the roofs of 
brick and cement houses 
most houses in the impoverished district have mudcoated bamboo 
walls and thatched roofs that wash away within a few hours whenever 
the jamuna floods 
azad said the jamuna has destroyed at least 20 villages in the 
past three years displacing 30000 inhabitants many of them 
resettled in neighboring districts or moved to cities he said 
last month the jamuna overflowed in at least 43 places during 
its 185mile journey from the hills in the north to the southern 
delta on the bay of bengal a water development board official said 
officials say privately that government efforts to tackle the 
annual deluge in the countryside have been halfhearted 
they say the focus of the flood control measures has been dhaka 
a city of six million people which was badly hit by floods in 
1988 at least 1400 people died nationwide in that years floods 
government officials speaking on condition of anonymity said 
president hussain muhammad ershads administration has spent the 
equivalent of about 31 million to build a giant earthen dam around 
dhaka 
in megaiya many residents are preparing to move 
on sunday workers began emptying the 13yearold granary and 
shopkeepers shifted their wares to another place one mile away 
in another five years the building we are sitting in may be 
gone if the river continues its destruction at the current rate 
almahmud the civil administrator said 
government officials and local activists apparently have no 
solution yet to the erosion 
we think we will have to live with it azad said 
