<TEXT>
most rural hospitals that have gone out of 
business were losing money because of their high operating costs 
rather than inadequate government subsidies congressional 
investigators say 
hospitals and members of congress have blamed a disparity in 
medicare payments to rural and urban hospitals for the financial 
plight of many rural facilities 
but a report by the general accounting office appears to support 
the bush administrations contention that rural hospitals are 
losing money primarily because their costs are too high 
medicare was not a major factor contributing to the financial 
decline and closure of most rural or urban hospitals that closed 
between 1985 and 1988 said the report released this week 
threefourths of the failed hospitals either profited from 
medicare patients or lost less money from treating them than other 
patients the report said 
under pressure from the health care industry congress last year 
decided to phase out the differential in medicare payments to rural 
and urban hospitals over five years the gap was cut from 12 
percent last year to 8 percent this year 
sen tom daschle dsd argued that inadequate medicare 
payments had cost rural hospitals money and reduced the health 
services to rural americans 
rep byron dorgan dnd introduced legislation this spring to 
eliminate the differential altogether next year 
most of the troubled hospitals are located in the central united 
states according to gao studies 
some 48 percent of the 140 rural hospitals that closed from 1985 
through 1988 were in texas and other south central states and 22 
percent were in the north central region 
failed rural hospitals usually are small and have low occupancy 
rates which contribute to their high operating costs the gao said 
hospitals that closed had occupancy rates 35 percent to 52 
percent lower than facilities that remained open the investigators 
said 
the investigators did say they could not rule out that medicare 
may have contributed disproportionately to the demise of some 
of the hospitals 
the department of health and human services inspector general 
found last year that more than 40 percent of rural hospitals made 
money on the medicare program because they operated at lower costs 
than other hospitals 
hospitals that were losing money tended to be smaller have 
lower occupancy rates and bigger stafftopatient ratios and keep 
patients longer according to that study 
</TEXT>
