<TEXT>
large increases in sales receipts for both 
crops and livestock are adding up to what the agriculture 
department sees as a banner year for farm income 
as charted by usda economists farm sales receipts make up the 
lions share of gross farm income big production and strong prices 
mean fat receipts 
government payments income from custom work sales of forest 
products and other miscellaneous cash sources account for the 
remainder 
on the other side of the ledger are farm expenses the costs of 
producing crops and livestock feed seed fertilizer interest and 
all the other related items go into that column 
in 1990 according to the departments economic research 
service farmers nationally may gross a record of 162 billion to 
168 billion from crops and livestock sales up from 158 billion 
in 1989 
livestock sales are expected to be in the range of 84 billion 
to 87 billion while crops sales are forecast at 77 billion to 
81 billion all figures are rounded 
not all products will share in the 1990 gains however the 
national figures also cloak the inequities farmers always face from 
one part of the country to another from one commodity to the next 
soybeans probably will be the only major crop showing smaller 
cash receipts in 1990 says economist diane bertelsen soybean 
prices are expected to be down about 15 percent from a year 
earlier and with little change in production soybean receipts are 
likely to be off 4 percent 
bertelsen writing in the july issue of agricultural outlook 
magazine said farmers will probably boost their sales of corn and 
other feed grains by 2 billion to 4 billion from last year 
fall corn prices are not expected to weaken as much as 
previously expected so the annual price could remain near last 
years average of 240 to 245 per bushel she said 
the price outlook reflects increased estimates of exports and 
domestic feed use despite a possible boost of 5 percent to 10 
percent in production this year tight supplies also are a 
contributing factor 
wheat production is expected to rise onethird this year while 
prices probably will be down 15 percent to 20 percent from last 
years level cash receipts for wheat cotton fruits and 
vegetables may be up less than 5 percent from 1989 
bertelsen said total livestock receipts in 1990 are forecast to 
rise by as much as 3 billion from last year to the forecast range 
of 84 billion to 87 billion 
reduced pork production and tight supplies are pushing hog 
prices up more than 20 percent from last years average while 
relatively stable beef production is likely to lead to a 3 percent 
to 4 percent increase in prices she said 
thus cattle and calf receipts may be up by as much 8 percent 
from last year while hog sales may rise by 20 percent 
poultry production is forecast to be up by about 7 percent in 
1990 although price declines of around 6 percent or 7 percent 
probably will keep total poultry and egg receipts flat at about 
15 billion bertelsen said 
looking at expenses the analyst said that prices of feed grain 
are showing less weakness than had been expected 
in the first quarter of this year economists thought the index 
of prices paid by farmers for feed would decline by 20 percent this 
year but now the decline is expected to be only half of that 
about 10 percent 
as a result 1990 spending for feed may decline only slightly 
this year and remain within 1 billion of 1989s 24 billion 
uncertainty about feed costs may be behind producers cautious 
approach to expanding herds despite higher hog and cattle 
prices bertelsen said 
spending for manufactured input items used in production 
overhead and operating expenses probably will increase 3 percent to 
5 percent this year interest expenses are expected to remain near 
15 billion for the third consecutive year 
meanwhile direct government payments to farmers probably will 
drop 2 billion or more to around 8 billion to 10 billion 
after adding up all the sales receipts and other figures 
deducting expenses and making other adjustments farmers nationally 
are expected to have a net cash income this year of 55 billion to 
59 billion compared with about 54 billion in 1989 the record 
was 572 billion in 1988 
by the agencys reckoning net cash income measures the value 
of commodities sold in a calendar year plus government payments 
less outofpocket costs some commodities sold actually may have 
been produced in earlier years and stored until marketed 
in another method of accounting the agency says net farm 
income may be in the range of 47 billion to 51 billion 
compared with last years record of 49 billion 
net farm income is used to measure the value of agricultural 
production whether sold or stored in a calendar year plus 
government payments minus all costs including depreciation and 
other allowances 
