prodded by west germany and france western countries are 
debating whether to come to the assistance of soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev and his crumbling economy western aid is 
widely seen as a way of easing soviet objections to a united 
germany being a member of the north atlantic treaty organization 
west germany already has agreed to pump 31 billion in loans 
into the soviet economy west european leaders agreed late last 
month to consider assistance for moscow but put aside a proposed 
15 billion aid package 
for his part gorbachev on wednesday gave himself and the soviet 
leadership two years to improve citizens lives or resign 
i think that in two years if there are no changes this 
leadership must go gorbachev told a tv interviewer as he entered 
the kremlin palace of congresses on the third day of the communist 
partys 28th congress 
it was the first time the soviet president and party leader who 
is facing bitter criticism from both radical reformers and party 
traditionalists has given himself and the leadership a deadline 
for turning around the countrys political economic and social 
problems 
on the eve of the london summit machine guntoting police 
guarded heathrow airports vip lounge and sharpshooters watched 
from the rooftops as a string of prime ministers foreign ministers 
and defense officials began arriving 
the early arrivals included the prime ministers of greece 
iceland denmark and spain canadian prime minster brian mulroney 
and secretary of state james a baker iii were arriving late 
wednesday 
security was expected to be even tighter on thursday during 
almost simultaneous arrivals by bush french president francois 
mitterrand and west german chancellor helmut kohl 
with the collapse of the sovietled warsaw pact nato is 
exploring ways to bring the nowoutdated military alliance into 
line with a changing world 
western leaders hope the changes will ease soviet concerns about 
east germany leaving the warsaw pact to join with west germany as a 
united nation in nato 
bush has proposed that nato leaders formally declare that 
nuclear weapons would be used only as a last resort a reversal of 
the 4decadeold policy favoring a firstuse nuclear option in the 
event of attack 
he also has recommended the eventual withdrawal of 1470 
nucleartipped artillery shells from europe and a reduction in nato 
forces along what is now west germanys eastern border 
western officials released some details of bushs proposals in 
advance perhaps to bolster gorbachev against conservative critics 
at a soviet party congress under way in moscow 
a senior british governnment source said mrs thatcher was cool 
to the idea of declaring nuclear arms as weapons of last resort 
and also was uneasy about the withdrawal of some 1400 nuclear 
artillery shells from europe 
referring to reduced eastwest tensions the source said the 
important thing is to recognize the enormity of the changes that 
have occurred but not to assume at the same time that all threats 
have disappeared 
in another step aimed at reassuring moscow west german defense 
ministry sources said in bonn that the government was willing to 
consider a soviet proposal that would limit the number of 
postunification german troops to about 400000 
that figure would correspond to the combined strengths of soviet 
and us forces in the region under a formula expected to be 
approved in conventional force reduction talks in vienna 
