<TEXT>
east german workers who have mounted warning 
strikes to press for higher wages and job security are only 
increasing the chances that their jobs will be eliminated west 
germanys economics minister says 
the minister helmut haussmann said in an interview published 
today by the newspaper die welt that east german industry must 
become more productive before its workers can afford to make 
demands 
in the next few weeks it will become clear who gets the upper 
hand psychologically whether its those who bring hope new jobs 
and a new way of life or the fearful and maybe even the 
malevolent he was quoted as saying 
lack of selfcontrol on the salary front will lead straight to 
unemployment haussmann said 
brief warning strikes involving up to 30000 people began 
monday the first work day after east and west germany formally 
merged their economies currencies and social welfare systems 
the east german news agency adn said several thousand metal and 
shipyard workers continued work stoppages on wednesday at plants in 
northern east germany 
the workers are demanding more pay better onthejob training 
and a guarantee that they will keep their jobs for at least two 
years adn said 
but there are few guarantees in the free market into which east 
germany is now entering and economists have predicted that up to 
one third of the former communist states 8000 businesses could 
fail 
the experts say as many as half of east germanys 8 million 
workers could lose their jobs under the pressure of competition 
from west germanys powerful and productive companies 
haussmann said some of this weeks strikes appeared to have been 
staged under remote control presumably from west germany 
whose powerful ig metall union has been helping its east german 
branch recruit thousands of members in recent weeks 
amid the labor unrest the east german cabinet set dec 2 as the 
date for electing members to an allgerman parliament and west 
germanys governing coalition gave its assent 
east germanys parliament still must approve it but that is 
unlikely to be an obstacle because prime minister lother de 
maizieres government has a parliamentary majority 
government sources said de maiziere would insist that elections 
for the allgerman parliament be kept separate from west german 
elections even if they occur on the same day 
the separation of the elections is an important issue because 
west german law requires political parties to win at least 5 
percent of the vote to obtain parliamentary representation 
there is no such law in east germany and some east german 
parties fear they would fail to reach the threshold if forced to 
compete in a single election in both countries 
west german interior minister wolfgang schaeuble said that if 
the 5 percent rule were applied in both countries but the ballots 
were tallied separately a party in west germany would need 2 
million votes for representation while in east germany only 
575000 would be needed 
there are about 40 million eligible voters in west germany and 
approximately 12 million in east germany 
immediately after the election east germany is expected to 
declare itself unified with west germany under the west german 
constitution 
on friday schaeuble and east german parliament state secretary 
guenther krause will begin talks in east berlin on a second state 
treaty to iron out the constitutional and legal aspects of final 
unification 
