<TEXT>
authorities in yugoslavias largest 
republic today dissolved the local legislature and government in 
its troubled southern province of kosovo the state news agency 
tanjug reported 
the move by the republic of serbia is likely to cause more 
unrest by the ethnic albanian majority in kosovo the nations 
least developed region 
the decision by all three chambers of the serbian parliament 
came in the wake of mondays declaration by 114 ethnic albanian 
deputies in kosovos provincial assembly to secede from serbia 
belgrade television said 
the document proclaimed kosovo equal in status to yugoslavias 
republics and declared that ethnic albanians the thirdlargest 
ethnic group in the country would no longer be considered a 
minority 
yugoslavia is a loose federation of six republics and two 
nominally autonomous provinces kosovo a province of 19 million 
90 percent of whom are ethnic albanian has progressively lost 
control of its affairs to serbia 
the decision to dissolve kosovos 188member legislature and the 
local government of premier jusuf zeinulahu was read to deputies 
during thursdays assembly session according to journalists in the 
provincial capital pristina 
delegates were informed that all elected officials in the 
regional government were suspended 
ethnic albanians seek restoration of the broader autonomy they 
enjoyed under a 1974 constitution that was amended in march 1989 
serbs who consider kosovo the cradle of their medieval kingdom 
claimed that ethnic albanians were pressuring the remaining slavs 
to move out of the province 
since the constitution was amended about 60 ethnic albanians 
have been killed in clashes with security forces 
ethnic albanians who have been demanding free elections and a 
multiparty system deny they discriminate against slavs in their 
province they say that claim has been used by serbias communist 
leader slobodan milosevic to gain popular support for his 
hardline policies 
serbias communist leadership is proposing a new state 
constitution that would effectively remove any vestige of 
selfgovernment enjoyed by its southern province the elimination 
of kosovos parliament under a new constitution would make ethnic 
albanians a small minority in the serbian parliament 
the decision to dissolve the regional parliament is an illegal 
one and the albanian people will not recognize it said ibrahim 
rugova leader of the democratic forum an ethnic albanian group 
that claims 500000 members 
serbia currently does not have any constitutional right to do 
such a thing he said adding that the forum would call on ethnic 
albanians to remain calm in the face of this provocation 
both the parliament and the government should continue to 
function normally because ethnic albanians have the majority 
he said 
serbian authorities also announced they were imposing 
unspecified extraordinary measures on pristinas radio and 
television as well as in the local telecommunications company 
tanjug reported it said the measures which appear designed to 
give serbia full control over the media will also extend to the 
albanianlanguage rilindia publishing house kosovos largest 
meanwhile results of a referendum held sunday and monday in 
serbia on whether to hold multiparty elections before adopting a 
new constitution showed 968 percent of the population voted for 
the government proposal to delay a free ballot the results of the 
vote in which some threequarters of serbias 67 million 
registered voters took part were released thursday 
opposition parties which demanded that elections be held before 
enactment of a new constitution had called on supporters to 
boycott the referendum 
yugoslavias northern republics of slovenia and croatia 
increasingly have sided with kosovo in its drive for autonomy from 
serbia 
this spring the republics held their first free elections in 45 
years for local legislatures both votes were won by centerright 
parties which trounced the communist parties that called the 
elections 
yugoslavias other three republics are scheduled to hold free 
elections later this year 
and on monday slovenias parliament proclaimed the states full 
sovereignty the declaration provides for an independent legal 
system that would take precedence over federal laws and for 
slovenian control of armed forces stationed in the republic 
slovenia the most prosperous of yugoslavias republics 
contains 2 million of the countrys 23 million population the 
republics new authorities demand that yugoslavia become a loose 
confederation of sovereign states 
but the communist government of serbia vehemently opposes 
turning yugoslavia into a confederation serbia also rejects 
westernstyle democracy for yugoslavia created in 1918 
