<TEXT>
here is an icy thought that oddly might make a 
hot summer seem even hotter the savings and loan bailout which 
could cost taxpayers 300 billion may be just the tip of the 
iceberg 
if the tip is equal to a sum of that size the single most 
expensive governmental cost in peacetime then how massive must the 
bulk of the berg be 
conceivably in the trillions of dollars says economist ronald 
utt who points out that financial obligations of agencies 
underwritten by the federal government now total 58 trillion 
and much of that obligation is in bad shape says utt vice 
president of the us chamber foundation a former employee of the 
white house office of management and budget and a former heritage 
foundation fellow 
potentially he says these financial obligations represent a 
staggering breakdown of government and a growing number of 
critics are saying the lack of public information on the matter 
represents a communications breakdown 
most people it seems safe to say cannot imagine that other 
financial breakdowns are threatened reasoning that if that were so 
they would have heard of them but that logic breaks as throroughly 
as the communications 
the obligations utt refers to are spread among deposit insurance 
programs loan and pension guarantees direct loan programs such as 
those administered by the small business administration and debts 
of five government enterprises 
utts chilling observations are contained in a paper written for 
heritage a conservative think tank whose opinions sometimes have 
been influential in the bush and reagan administrations 
the federal savings and loan insurance corp says utt is by no 
means the only federal credit program confronted with huge losses 
the federal deposit insurance corp and federal housing 
administration lost money in 1988 and 1989 and seemed destined to 
lose again in 1990 the fha he says has seen the level of claims 
against its shrinking reserves rise nearly three times in three 
years 
further he states half of the farm loans made by the farmers 
home administration are in default and half of these defaulted 
loans have been in that condition for more than three years 
on and on it goes 
the federal government he notes stands behind nearly 500 
billion in guaranteed veterans administration and fha mortgages 
48 billion in guaranteed student loans 
and a host of other guarantees ranging from rural 
electrification to shipbuilding loans and from small business 
disaster loans to loans for building plants to convert grain to 
ethanol 
all together he estimates the contingent liability associated 
with loan and deposit guarantees totaled 35 trillion at the end 
of fiscal 1988 and other insurance programs flood insurance for 
instance add 500 billion more 
how could such massive obligations not rise to the surface and 
break more forcefully into the media how can such dangers lurk so 
near and not cause more concern 
utt doesnt have an answer to those questions but he does 
suggest that both congress and taxpayers played a role 
most lawmakers he says tried to convince americans that the 
crisis was just an isolated incident and that the vast bulk of the 
government credit programs are wellmanaged and pose little risk to 
the taxpayer 
and for their part many taxpayers have wished this to be so 
it isnt says utt who advocates passage of an omnibus credit 
solvency act to fundamentally restructure these many programs in 
order to reduce taxpayer exposure to costly program failures 
before it is too late he adds 
