<TEXT>
the changes in europes political landscape the past year make 
this nato summit one of the most significant in the alliances 
41year history here at a glance is a look at where the north 
atlantic treaty organization has been and where it may go 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the nato treaty was signed april 4 1949 in washington in it 
the united states canada and 10 european nations belgium 
britain denmark france iceland italy luxembourg the 
netherlands norway and portugal aligned themselves against any 
military threat from the soviet union greece turkey west germany 
and spain later joined the alliance 
the treaty says the parties agree that an armed attack 
against one or more of them in europe or north america shall be 
considered an attack against them all 
france spain and iceland are not part of natos integrated 
military structure 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
nato seeks to maintain enough military forces to deter an attack 
from the seven nations of the sovietled warsaw pact while at the 
same time striving for disarmament and detente 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the alliance is the military protector of 620 million people 
3528 million in western europe 2422 million in the united states 
and 256 million canadians 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the warsaw pact is a military alliance created may 14 1955 its 
members are the soviet union east germany poland czechoslovakia 
hungary bulgaria and romania 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the berlin wall has fallen the german economy has merged free 
elections have replaced most of the totalitarian leaders of eastern 
and central europe and red army troops and tanks are preparing to 
go home how can nato after four decades as a military alliance 
poised against the warsaw pact transform itself into a mostly 
political organization following the collapse of communism in 
eastern europe 
nato leaders are expected to order a review to develop a 
negotiating position for reducing shortrange nuclear weapons in 
talks with moscow the kremlin suggests that those negotiations 
begin this fall but nato insists that they take place only after 
an agreement to reduce tanks artillery and other conventional 
forces in europe 
the ministers are expected to nudge negotiators from the east 
and west to wrap up the slowmoving conventional arms talks and 
pledge to make even deeper cuts in a later round of discussions 
they also will likely discuss the strategy of forward defense 
brought into question by the prospect of a united germany 
forward defense refers to the stationing of troops to defend the 
front line during an attack the idea is to defend territory at its 
border and not give up any land to invading soldiers the border 
between east and west germany has historically been considered part 
of the front line but it is soon to be erased 
