conferees are expected to agree that two layers of steel are the 
best barrier between crude oil and the environment but 
environmentalists say they worry that smaller barges will be 
exempt which could imperil rivers and ocean harbors particularly 
in new england where traffic is heavy and sea beds are rocky 
were concerned because the smaller barges get into 
semienclosed bodies of water ecosystems they could destroy with 
just a small spill said clifton curtis of the environmental 
group friends of the earth 
congressional staffers environmentalists and shipping industry 
lobbyists say it is clear what the final version of the legislation 
will look like they expect a requirement that new tankers and 
oceangoing barges weighing over 5000 gross tons have double hulls 
which consist of a second layer of steel and an airspace between 
the sea and the cargo older vessels would have to be either phased 
out of operation or refitted with second hulls 
at this point the double hull requirement is a foregone 
conclusion said a house staffer who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
but curtis and other environmentalists cite coast guard 
statistics that indicate a majority of spills involve barges under 
5000 gross tons in 1988 for example 68 percent of the tanker or 
barge oil pollution incidents investigated by the coast guard 
involved the smaller vessels 
statistics compiled by the lexington mass consulting firm 
temple barker amp sloane inc show that of 310 oilcarrying barges 
only 72 are in the heavier weight group that under the house bill 
would be required to have double hulls by the year 2015 
ernie corrado president of the american institute of merchant 
marine shipping said the tanker operators represented by his group 
realize that new barges either foreign or domestic will be 
required to have double hulls 
weve accepted that he said 
corrado said owners already have begun ordering new vessels with 
double hulls 
but corrados group and others argue that double hulls also 
carry risks gases trapped between the hull walls could cause an 
explosion and a breach in the outer wall could allow water in the 
cavity between the hulls capsizing the vessel 
the national academy of sciences is working on a study expected 
to detail some of the weaknesses of double hulls the senate wants 
to give the secretary of transportation authority to review that 
study along with other data to see if alternatives to double hulls 
would work as well or better 
its not simply a question of economics its a question of 
safety said joe farrell president of the american waterways 
operators a trade association representing coastal shippers 
including oil barge haulers 
the oil spill legislation has been debated in congress for 15 
years but efforts to pass it out were stepped up after the exxon 
valdez spill of march 24 1989 the super tanker ran aground on 
bligh reef in alaska spilling 11 million gallons of crude oil into 
prince william sound 
less sensational but still damaging to the environment have been 
barge spills in new york harbor and buzzards bay mass 
among other provisions the bill would create a 1 billion 
cleanup fund through a 5cent tax on each barrel of oil created in 
or imported to the united states it also would establish coast 
guard oil spill response centers along us coasts 
the doublehull provision is among the few remaining issues in 
dispute between the house and senate 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

