<DOCNO> AP900705-0077 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
weather changes caused by unusual pacific 
ocean currents may have led scientists to overestimate how much the 
earth has warmed up in recent decades according to a new study 
but says the author it may be that global warming helped cause 
those changes in the ocean 
jim angell of the national oceanic and atmospheric 
administration has calculated the amount of global warming 
associated with the el nino events over the last couple of decades 
subtracting the ocean effects reduces the global warming by 
onefourth between the 1960s and the 1980s according to angells 
report being published friday in geophysical research letters a 
journal published by the american geophysical union 
but he cautions against quick assumptions about which is cause 
and which effect 
it may be that part of the increase in global warming is a 
result of the strength of the el nino events in the 1980s but it 
may also be that the global warming led to more and stronger el 
ninos angell said in a telephone interview 
concern about global warming has grown in recent years with 
many scientists worried that increasing carbon dioxide and other 
gases in the atmosphere will act like a greenhouse overheating the 
planet 
scientists have estimated that the layer of air closest to the 
earth warmed by 033 degrees celsius 059 degrees fahrenheit 
between the 1960s and the 1980s 
several of the warmest years recorded occurred in the 1980s a 
time when at least two of the socalled el nino events also took 
place 
angell of noaas air resources lab in silver spring md noted 
that ocean warming in el ninos can contribute to changes in global 
temperature 
el nino events involve unusually warm water moving eastward in 
the pacific ocean they can affect weather events worldwide during 
their lifetime of a year or so the strongest el nino in at least a 
century occurred in 198283 and a milder one took place in 198788 
angell found that after subtracting the effect of the el nino 
warming from the record the air had warmed by 024 degrees celsius 
043 degrees fahrenheit 27 percent less than the original 
calculations 
in addition 1988 is no longer the warmest year on record being 
only slightly hotter than the overall average angell concluded in 
the journal article 
subtracting the effects of the el nino also cuts in half the 
annual variations in global temperature angell explained and 
makes it easier to see the cooling that results from volcanic 
eruptions 
scientists had expected the eruptions of the indonesian volcano 
agung in 1963 and mexicos el chichon in 1982 to cool the globe 
because of their smoke and ash blocking sunlight 
no cooling was apparent however which prompted angells study 
he found that the warming effect of el nino swamped the cooling 
from the volcanoes in the original record when the el nino warming 
is deleted the volcanic effects become much more obvious he 
explained 
the el nino is named with the spanish word for the christ child 
because it was first noticed by south american fishermen and 
generally occurs around christmas time 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

