<DOCNO> AP900705-0101 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
top pentagon officials will develop plans to 
streamline the varied financial and accounting operations for the 
armed services and defense agencies it was announced on thursday 
at present army navy air force marine corps and defense 
agency operations function independently 
deputy defense secretary donald atwood has instructed senior 
pentagon officials to develop organizational plans to consolidate 
the operations under the direction of the departments comptroller 
a pentagon statement said 
those officials who are scheduled to begin their work next 
week will submit plans to defense secretary dick cheney for 
approval within the next six months 
the consolidation comes as part of cheneys muchtouted defense 
management review an attempt to make the department more efficient 
amid the nations budget constraints 
the statement said the services and agencies have their own 
operations policies management and overhead structures develop 
and use their own accounting and finance systems and set many of 
their own priorities 
there is a great need within the department for 
standardization of financial and accounting information the 
integrated organization will enable us to use our limited 
resources with greater efficiency the statement quoted atwood as 
saying 
the new organization will encompass centers that employ 7000 
civilians and 500 military personnel 
they include 
army finance and accounting center indianapolis ind 
navy accounting and finance center crystal city va 
navy finance center cleveland ohio 
marine crops finance center kansas city mo 
air force accounting and finance center denver colo 
defense logistics agency finance center columbus ohio 
washington headquarters services finance and accounting 
operations pentagon 
those are the centers that oversee the pay going to the nations 
active reserve and retired military officers they also supervise 
the civilians who work for the department and administer payments 
to defense contractors transportation and travel payments 
accounting and reporting to the treasury department and the office 
of management and budget 
the changes will not immediately affect positions at the various 
centers but one of the objectives is to reduce cost we expect 
the work force to be smaller in the long run defense department 
spokesman bill caldwell said 
streamlining the centers into one organization will mean fewer 
jobs but positions will be pared in increments primarily 
through attrition and retraining personnel to fill positions in 
other areas where ever feasible caldwell said 
he said a savings of 150 million annually is anticipated when 
the operation is fully implemented an estimate that amounts to 
slightly less than 10 per cent of the current operational costs 
the savings estimate was derived from a study of the major 
functions that will be consolidated the official said 
although upfront costs for the consolidation could run over 
100 million they are expected to be offset in the long run the 
official said 
no decision has been made on where the new organization will be 
located 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

