<TEXT>
communist party leaders will consider a proposal 
to change their partys name in order to regain the peoples trust 
a spokesman said thursday 
col gen dmitri volkogonov a prominent historian proposed 
that the party change its name to something like the party of 
democratic socialism spokesman alexander lebedev said 
however the idea was unlikely to win support at the 
4657member party congress a poll by the congress sociological 
service found it reported that 80 percent of delegates favored 
keeping the name as it is and only 14 percent backed changing it 
according to the nightly news program vremya 
but volkogonov a threestar general who has written 
groundbreaking biographies of josef stalin and leon trotsky told 
the congress section on party renewal that the name change was 
inevitable 
in his volkogonovs words even if the proposal doesnt find 
support now in two or three years it will nonetheless be necessary 
to take this step lebedev reported 
the proposal came at a section meeting that was closed to 
journalists 
lebedev said volkogonov also argued that the current party name 
was a legacy from stalin the historian said communist ideals have 
turned out to be a lovely utopia whereas socialism deals with 
more immediate attainable goals 
the renaming is not a goal in itself but its needed to 
restore peoples trust lebedev quoted volkogonov as saying he 
spoke at a briefing thursday evening 
the section decided the proposal should be brought to the floor 
of the congress lebedev said without specifying when it will be 
addressed 
several eastern european communist parties have changed their 
names or even disbanded in the past year in a struggle to retain 
vestiges of their former power amid political upheaval 
the congress which began monday and is scheduled to run for 10 
days comes at a time of crisis for the soviet party it is not in 
immediate danger of losing its dominance of the political scene 
but its authority is at an extreme low members are reported 
quitting by the thousands and radical communists have talked of 
splitting off and forming a new party 
the congress meeting in the kremlins massive palace of 
congresses is technically the highest organ of the communist 
party empowered to set the party line change the leadership and 
revamp the partys entire structure 
it broke into several sections thursday after three days of 
plenary meetings at which mikhail s gorbachev the party leader 
and president underwent a barrage of criticism for flaws in his 
reforms but also received repeated votes of personal support 
lebedev reported that in other action 
many delegates urged a sweeping turnover in the partys top 
leadership perhaps by as much as 90 percent 
deputy prime minister leonid abalkin received heavy criticism 
for his speech wednesday in which he maintained that if the 
communist party does not support the countrys switch from a 
planned to a market economy it will be left on the sidelines of 
history 
gorbachev who sat in on the section on agriculture urged the 
party to talk less and do more the party has to understand that 
its monopoly is over and it has to prove its right to an 
avantgarde role with deeds he reportedly said 
several highranking officers accused the party of propagating 
a foreign policy that led to the loss of eastern europe and the 
weakening of the nations defenses others defended the countrys 
foreign policy as victorious 
earlier thursday a local communist official said gorbachev had 
acknowledged to a meeting of his colleagues that the kremlin cast 
them adrift as it rapidly switched signals in a bid to quiet 
republics demands for autonomy 
filip stroganov a party leader from the baltic republic of 
latvia said gorbachev had converted him from an opponent to a 
supporter during a meeting with more than 300 district and regional 
officials late wednesday 
i like people with character stroganov told reporters 
yesterday i saw his character 
stroganov said that regional leaders complained that gorbachev 
and the central leadership changed their minds too often on a new 
structure to bind the soviet unions republics together 
latvias neighbor lithuania already has declared independence 
the parliament of latvia and the third baltic republic estonia 
have signaled their intention to follow 
we dont have a clear position on this question stroganov 
said the lack of a precise position on this issue put us in an 
awkward situation 
gorbachev agreed with this yesterday he said the regional 
leaders had been pressing for a meeting for more than two years 
and gorbachev also acknowledged it had been a mistake to put it off 
for so long he said 
