<TEXT>
about 5300 rebels fought government 
troops in monrovias suburbs thursday according to an insurgent 
source in neighboring ivory coast while soldiers ransacked stores 
and restaurants 
president samuel does advisers continued to desert as the 
rebels tightened their grip on the capital on wednesday does 
most trusted commander lt gen charles julu left liberia 
weakening the presidents already fragile position us officials 
in washington said 
meanwhile a senior rebel leader in the united states accused 
the us administration of trying to prevent rebel leader charles 
taylor from taking power and said the rebels would not halt their 
advance to permit peace talks 
in the citys eastern and western suburbs growing numbers of 
rebels battled soldiers for a fourth consecutive day the rebels 
now control all roads into monrovia 
rebel sources in ivory coast said the 800man contingent that 
attacked the capitals suburbs was reinforced by 4500 others the 
reinforcments brought up heavy armaments captured from army bases 
outside monrovia 
the rebel source said the insurgents took schiefflin the 
military camp 12 miles east of monrovia the rebels estimated doe 
still had 2000 fighting men in the capital 
for the first time since the fighting began the christian 
missionary station elwa did not broadcast thursday evening it 
broadcasts several times a day for several hours the station is on 
the outskirts of monrovia 
in monrovia government troops shot their way into stores 
warehouses and restaurants under cover of curfew and emptied the 
shelves in the early hours of thursday 
soldiers roamed the streets in stolen cars firing in the air to 
frighten people and keep them back while they looted the only 
vehicles on the streets were driven by soldiers who left dead and 
wounded civilians by the roadside 
as morning broke frightened monrovians ventured out into 
deserted streets and discovered at least 16 bodies 
a man with three bullet wounds bled for four hours in the citys 
main waterfront market despite pleas to soldiers to carry him to 
the hospital 
monrovias main john f kennedy hospital which like the rest of 
the city has been without water and power for more than a week has 
been abandoned by doctors and nurses and most of its patients 
a serious food shortage in monrovia has forced people to beg for 
rice give us food we are dying one man said 
rebel leader tom woewiyu based in the united states said the 
bush administration failed to keep a promise to force doe out if 
the rebels held off from attacking the capital 
the us has had ample opportunity to take this man out 
but for some reason they dont want to do that maybe they want 
to see a government evolve that does not have taylor involved in 
it i dont know why hes an unknown factor i suppose 
woewiyu said senior state department officials who had supported 
doe during his 10year rule were trying to intervene to help him 
again now the state department has said it questions taylors 
commitment to democracy 
doe in his heavily guarded executive mansion said tuesday he 
would resign if his safety and that of his krahn tribe were 
guaranteed but so far he has shown no sign of leaving 
in monrovia soldiers fired on fishermen in canoes off the 
coast claiming they were transporting rebels 
shipping sources said 250000 tons of rice bound for the 
stricken city is on board a ship the sea star steaming among us 
navy ships off monrovia the captain reportedly feared the ship 
would be ransacked if it docked 
the sources also said a ship carrying 5000 tons of rice put in 
at the rebelheld port of buchanan the britishowned rizcup 
enterprise was hijacked by rebels off monrovia last week 
health workers said young children and old people in buchanan 
were falling sick and risked dying of starvation last week workers 
at a nearby rubber plantation were eating pig feed after food had 
run out 
in monrovia the food shortage has forced people to forage for 
leaves and roots on patches of wasteland throughout the city 
meanwhile julu head of the security unit assigned to protect 
doe fled to neighboring sierra leone he had been chief of staff 
only since the weekend resignation of lt gen henry dubar who 
also fled liberia 
julu led army troops who killed more than 2000 civilians in 
northern liberia after an unsuccessful coup attempt against doe 
liberia was founded in 1847 by freed american slaves and their 
descendents who ruled the county until doe seized power in april 
1980 in a violent coup liberia was black africas first 
independent nation 
