<TEXT>
the nato allies on thursday searched for a way to 
draw east european countries including the soviet union closer to 
the western alliance without giving away military secrets 
president bush suggested at the opening session of the two day 
summit of nato leaders the establishment of liaison offices between 
nations in the sovietled warsaw pact and the alliance according 
to white house spokesman marlin fitzwater 
the general purpose is to find some way to give them access to 
nato in a learning capacity and hopefully one in which they would 
appreciate where were coming from he said 
a diplomatic source who demanded anonymity said bush 
emphasized that the warsaw pact officials would not sit at the 
table with us 
the novel idea is one of a number of proposals being floated by 
the united states and other countries to revamp the north atlantic 
treaty organization to respond to diminished eastwest tensions 
the allies want to make nato created in 1949 in an era of 
hostility and suspicion appear less threatening to the kremlin in 
doing so they hope to encourage soviet president mikhail gorbachev 
to drop his objections to membership in the alliance for a united 
germany 
west germany is an influential member of nato but east germany 
belongs to the sovietled warsaw pact 
the idea of creating a special diplomatic status for the east 
european countries reflects the wests uncertainty about how to 
deal with its former adversaries 
the european community the trading bloc of a dozen west 
european nations also is struggling to give the emerging 
democracies as much economic help as possible short of full 
membership 
it has come up with the idea of associate memberships 
nato too doesnt see its onetime enemies becoming new 
recruits 
were going to have to investigate ways of helping these 
countries be part of a bigger whole without necessarily having 
them become parts of the organization said a senior nato 
diplomat demanding anonymity 
we dont in any way want to give hungary poland 
czechoslovakia for example the sense that theyre being left 
out he said but at the same time we cant officially bring 
them in 
officials dont want to upset the balance of power in europe and 
leave the soviet union still a formidable military power without 
allies 
for the soviet union not only having a united germany in nato 
but having some eastern european countries in nato would be perhaps 
a bit much to swallow said the nato diplomat 
jane sharp senior researcher at the stockholm international 
peace research institute in sweden said the big problem now is 
not to exclude and isolate the russians taking east european 
countries into nato probably is not a good idea 
even hungary which intends to withdraw from the warsaw pact by 
late next year isnt rushing to join 
hungary does not want to make the european security situation 
less stable than it is today hungarian foreign minister geza 
jeszenszky said after a recent visit to nato 
even if it were possible politically for us to think about 
applying for membership in nato that would be not conducive to 
security right now he said 
but there are ways to create closer links 
i would expect nato to strengthen and thicken its ties with 
likeminded states and reforming states said a nato official 
demanding anonymity 
us officials have said hungary has quietly proposed to nato 
participating as an observer in political or nonmilitary 
committees 
fitzwater said details of bushs proposal have yet to be fleshed 
out 
but he said it could mean inviting the warsaw pact countries to 
have an observer status at nato let them set up temporary or 
permanent liaison offices or attend meetings 
no nations outside of the alliance currently have such a status 
nato officials said 
many countries including the united states and the soviet 
union have separate missions to the european community even 
though they are not members moscow opened its liaison office last 
year 
by doing so they can keep closer tabs on the communitys 
business and increase contacts with trading bloc officials the 
united states also uses its mission to voice complaints over trade 
policies 
at nato east european diplomats might be able to sit on some of 
the many conferences it holds yearly on a range of topics 
the alliance has panels on science and technology economics and 
one on the challenges of modern society 
there has been a greater trend toward openness with the east 
since 1986 military observers from warsaw pact nations have 
attended western war games 
last december soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze made 
an unprecedented visit to nato headquarters in brussels belgium 
since then the foreign ministers of poland hungary and 
czechoslovakia have stopped by east german foreign minister markus 
meckel will do so next week 
</TEXT>
