<TEXT>
the oneparty government on thursday 
broadened its crackdown on proponents of multiparty democracy 
arresting four more prominent kenyans including the son of a 
former vice president 
the wives of two detained opposition leaders pleaded with 
president daniel arap mois government to refrain from torture in 
what appeared to be the harshest crackdown since 1982 
thursdays arrests of three lawyers and of the son of a former 
vice president brought to at least 11 the number of people 
detained since wednesday by the singleparty government according 
to detainees families and other sources close to opposition 
figures 
several other prominent kenyans went into hiding thursday night 
the arrests follow months of official criticism of those calling 
for reform and come in advance of a rumored rally for multiparty 
democracy that the government has vowed to prevent 
two of those detained former cabinet ministers kenneth matiba 
and charles rubia had asked the government for permission to hold 
a meeting saturday in support of legalizing political opposition 
which has been outlawed since 1982 
their request was not granted but rumor has been widespread in 
this east african capital that crowds might nonetheless appear and 
moi has warned people against attending any meeting 
matiba and rubia were seized wednesday by plainclothes security 
agents in a press release thursday their wives edith matiba and 
hannah rubia said that our husbands arrest is intended to force 
curtailment of the multiparty debate and stop lawful and peaceful 
changes which are crucial if kenya is to avoid the well trodden 
path of so many other african states 
the women noting the unexplained slaying in february of kenyas 
foreign minister said they were extremely worried about their 
husbands lives and about ill treatment the men might receive 
we appeal to the kenyan government not to torture our 
husbands they said 
their statement reflected the heightening tensions that calls 
for political pluralism have brought to kenya a country best known 
for stability and democracy on a troubled continent 
since the beginning of the year a loose coalition emboldened by 
the changes in eastern europe has repeatedly accused the ruling 
kenya african national union party of intolerance corruption and 
electionrigging the government has flatly rejected any move 
toward multiple parties and cabinet ministers have called those 
backing such moves subversives 
moi who has ruled kenya since 1978 has repeatedly threatened 
arrests vowing to hunt down political pluralists like rats in 
a statement tuesday he said the government would use force if 
necessary to halt activities it deems subversive 
the government has talked tough now it apparently has decided 
to act tough said a western diplomat speaking on condition he 
not be identified further when asked about the recent arrests 
the american embassy in nairobi said thursday it was following 
the situation with interest and concern 
later thursday lawyer john khaminwa was detained at the 
provincial police headquarters mrs matiba and mrs rubia said 
mohamed ibrahim who is with a law firm whose members have been 
critical of the government also was detained thursday according 
to the englishlanguage newspaper daily nation 
raila odinga son of former vice president oginga odinga was 
arrested at his office said gibson kamau kuria a human rights 
lawyer the younger odinga whose father is still seen as a 
potential rival to the government despite being removed from the 
vice presidency in the 1960s has already twice been held for 
lengthy periods by mois government 
late thursday about 10 police seized gitobu iminyara a lawyer 
who edits a monthly magazine that often criticizes the government 
on human rights issues 
kuria the human rights lawyer was one of several prominant 
kenyans who went into hiding late thrusday 
five associates of matiba including his driver two bodyguards 
and two personal assistants also were detained late wednesday 
according to matibas office 
kenyan law permits police to hold people without charge for up 
to 14 days late thursday the government said it was holding matiba 
and rubia under public security statutes but made no mention of 
the other detainees matibas daughter julie said the family had 
no word on where he was being held 
kenya has been a de facto oneparty state since the last 
opposition party led by the elder odinga was banned in 1969 a 
1982 constitutional amendment declared it a oneparty state 
later that year the government arrested scores of people 
following a failed coup 
