majority and the roman catholic minority 
selfgovernment was among the casualties of the violence that 
erupted in northern ireland in the late 1960s what began as a 
civil rights campaign by the catholic minority against economic and 
political discrimination escalated into sectarian conflict 
the british army was sent into the province in 1969 and the 
british government suspended the ulster parliament in 1972 
assuming direct rule of the province 
the angloirish agreement signed in 1985 guaranteed the irish 
government a say in northern irelands affairs as part of a process 
designed to promote peace in the province 
the agreement provoked an angry reaction from the protestant 
unionist parties which want northern ireland to remain linked with 
britain they broke off all contacts with the british government in 
protest 
it is a measure of brookes success that the unionist leaders 
are participating in talks which inevitably will involve some 
participation by dublin 
brooke has been talking with protestant and roman catholic 
leaders in northern ireland in an effort to reach an agreement on 
opening formal negotiations these contacts have not included sinn 
fein the legal political arm of the outlawed irish republican army 
the ira has been fighting to push the british out of northern 
ireland unite the province with the republic of ireland and set 
up an allireland socialist state 
since the british army was sent to northern ireland in 1969 
about 2800 people have been killed in the violence 
about 60 percent of northern irelands 15 million are 
protestant most of the remaining 40 percent are catholic 
