<TEXT>
regulators on thursday sought a record 24 
million from the former chairman of a large california thrift 
institution accused of squandering deposits on luxury condominiums 
trips to europe and a gun collection 
the office of thrift supervision said it was seeking 19 million 
in restitution and 5 million in penalties from thomas spiegel the 
former chairman of columbia savings and loan association in beverly 
hills calif 
spiegel a close associate of former drexel burnham lambert junk 
bond chief michael milken built the institution into one of the 
nations largest thrifts it had the industrys largest portfolio 
of highyield highrisk junk bonds valued at 37 billion at the 
end of 1989 
spiegel denied the charges and accused the agency of conducting 
a politicallymotivated trial by press release 
meanwhile edward harshfield columbias current chief 
executive said in a statement that the institutions current 
management cooperated with the thrift office and said the 
allegations do not reflect on current management or the institution 
as a whole 
columbia is still operating but analysts predict junk bond 
losses will eventually force government seizure 
the 19 million in restitution if recovered would go to the 
thrift while the 5 million penalty would go to the us treasury 
regulators ordered spiegel to establish an escrow account or 
provide other security guaranteeing payment if their allegations 
are upheld 
they are seeking return of 29 million for an unauthorized 
bonus 463000 for improper personal expenses 64 million for 
corporate aircraft and a luxury hangar 11 million for luxury 
condominiums in resort areas 57 million for loans to a friend 
and the use of luxury cars and 24 million for unauthorized 
payments to a charitable foundation spiegel controlled 
the personal expenses include 7000 spent on tickets for a 
michael jackson concert 2000 on a winetasting course for 
spiegel and his wife and 55000 for a gun collection that 
included uzi submachine guns the thrift office said 
it said columbia lost 57 million on 28 million in loans to 
luxury auto dealer howard schneider who allowed spiegel to use 
several of his cars it also said spiegel used the thrifts 
condominiums in jackson hole wyo indian wells calif and park 
city utah and that milkens brother lowell frequently used the 
jackson hole condo 
the corporate jets and hangar were built in a partnership with 
michael milken who often used the aircraft for his personal use 
regulators said 
