a kashrut license certifies that food served in an establishment 
is kosher that is it conforms to jewish dietary law the 
certification is considered crucial as most observant jews will 
not eat in nonkosher establishments 
in israel belly dancing is a popular form of entertainment for 
special occasions but it has become part of the battleground 
between israels secular majority and a religious minority which 
wants the jewish state to observe strict orthodox law 
in the past rabbis routinely threatened to take certificates 
away from establishments where belly dancers performed saying they 
violated religious notions of modesty said lawyer neta goldman of 
the association for civil rights in israel 
but in late may she obtained a court ruling prohibiting rabbis 
from withholding certificates for offences unrelated to food 
rabbis now get around the court ruling by threatening to cancel 
kosher certificates on trumpedup charges that food is not prepared 
according to dietary law complained lea davish who runs a middle 
eastern dance school 
