<TEXT>
shigeyuki hashimoto says just watching the 
pace of modern japanese life makes him tired but he has a rare 
perspective hashimoto spent 45 years as a guerrilla fighter in the 
malaysian jungle 
he was working in malaya when world war ii ended and joined 
guerrillas of the malaya communist party 
i always missed japan and always wanted to come back but to 
do so would require a surrender hashimoto said in an interview 
japanese people in my generation were taught that surrender was 
more disgraceful than death 
hashimoto 71 and 79yearold kiyoaki tanaka emerged from 
jungle sanctuaries on the malaysiathailand border in january when 
the communist guerrillas ended one of the worlds longest 
insurgencies 
belief in the shame of surrender made fierce fighters of 
japanese soldiers and motivated a few to hold out on remote islands 
long after the war ended the last member of the japanese imperial 
army to surrender was lt hiroo onoda who gave up in the 
philippines in 1974 
hashimoto and tanaka were not in the wartime army but were 
working for a japanese ironworks in malaya when the war ended they 
joined the guerrillas fighting british colonial troops first and 
after malaysian independence in 1957 the noncommunist government 
japan invaded malaya and other southeast asian countries 
during the pacific war claiming it would free the region from the 
colonization of european countries and the united states but 
history has proven that what japan really did in the region was not 
better than what other invaders had done hashimoto said in an 
inverview 
after japan surrendered i thought about what i could do 
for malayas independence and decided to help the communist forces 
which were also fighting for independence he said 
japan may have surrendered but we were still fighting a war 
against britain i was never a communist but we fought for a 
common goal they also accepted us very warmly 
hashimoto said he was one of seven japanese civilians and about 
14 soldiers who joined the guerrillas in 1945 and that only he and 
tanaka survived 
he would not give details about the many years in the tropical 
jungle but said life there was quite comfortable because it was 
never cold and there was plenty of food 
we ate almost everything including the meat of elephants 
tigers monkeys and wild pigs he said 
since his return to japan hashimoto has lived with his younger 
brother noriyuki in a twobedroom apartment in chiba just east 
of tokyo he is not eligible for a veterans pension but said a 
small welfare payment was enough for his modest needs 
he said he rises before dawn as he did in the jungle and goes 
for a walk around the town then spends the day reading and 
watching television 
beginning in 1970 the guerrillas had shortwave radio and 
hashimoto learned of his homelands postwar redevelopment i knew 
japan had fully recuperated from the destruction of the war and had 
become a major economic power he said 
even so the modern scene amazed him 
i never saw that many people and cars in my life he said 
it got me tired just by looking at them people in the street 
were also walking very fast 
of japans proper role in the world he said we should always 
think in terms of whats good for the rest of the world as well as 
whats good for japan 
one country should never cause troubles in other countries for 
the sake of its own gains in that sense it was wrong for japan to 
expand to the southeast asia in the way it did and start the 
pacific war against the united states 
freedom he said is a beautiful thing but my feeling is that 
some people are taking the spirit of freedom wrongly and thinking 
they are free to do anything i think it is important for us to 
know that real freedom should not cause troubles for others 
hashimoto said he would spend his remaining days visiting 
relatives of fallen comrades 
i am too old to start something new but i want to go around 
japan to meet families of my colleagues and tell them how they were 
doing in the jungle he said 
</TEXT>
