<TEXT>
dramatically larger crops have brought 
television and motorbikes to oncepoor villages and turned a nation 
with chronic food shortages into the worlds thirdranking rice 
exporter 
nature has been kind the past two years but the engine for 
growth has been the communist partys retreat from the disaster of 
collective agriculture and adoption of freemarket policies that 
gave farmers incentives 
vietnams rice boom may be the biggest success story of the 
economic reforms many communistruled countries adopted in recent 
years industry and other sectors of the vietnamese economy have 
fared poorly 
truong cong tin deputy director of the government institute of 
agricultural science of south vietnam said agriculture appears 
able to lift vietnams overall economic development about 80 
percent of the 65 million vietnamese work on the land 
aid officials said the progress in traditionally impoverished 
villages of the north may help reduce the huge flow boat people 
out of the country 
in 1988 the north imported 300000 tons of rice and appealed 
for emergency foreign aid for provinces where millions of people 
were hungry because of devastating typhoons officials said some 
farmers had to eat their rice seed stocks 
now the north feeds itself for the first time in decades and 
last year even exported about 40000 tons of rice said tran bach 
ngoc an official of the state rice export company vinafood the 
south produced the rest of the record 14 million tons of rice 
exported 
officials said vietnam had exported about 600000 tons of rice 
in the first half of 1990 and the years total might surpass 1989 
they said improvements such as replacing antiquated milling 
machines could make vietnam a threat to thailand and the united 
states the leading exporters 
before we worked in the fields very regularly sometimes 
eight hours a day but we didnt work very hard said le minh re 
51 of da ton village on the outskirts of hanoi the national 
capital in the north 
we did not get the amount of rice equal to the effort now if 
we work hard we will have more rice and can use it for our own 
needs now even some city people rush here to rent out land from 
the cooperative to farm 
re is starting a lucrative silkworm industry and building a 
house for his son 
brick houses have replaced most thatched huts in da ton and a 
new school was built last year farmers who once took their goods 
to market on bicycles use japanesemade motorcycles one of every 
five families has television 
some bought blackandwhite tvs and now theyve changed to 
color said the head of the cooperative le van bui during the 
interview he was distracted occasionally by the latemorning soap 
opera 
bui and other officials identified the key reform as communist 
party resolution 10 adopted in april 1988 after several years of 
poor production 
resolution 10 gave farmers longterm leases on the land 
encourageing them to enrich it it also reduced the role of the 
cooperative so farmers would do most of the work individually not 
as part of unmotivated work groups 
today cooperatives like the one at da ton are involved in 
helping farmers get supplies and technical aid not in actual 
production 
improving a system introduced in 1981 authorities also 
increased the amount of the crop farmers could sell on the free 
market and low prices paid by the state were brought into line 
with the free market 
greater state investment and technical improvements increased 
production particularly in the mekong delta of the south where 
one of the worlds great rivers nourishes verdant ricelands 
last year the government provided irrigation for about 250000 
acres of rice paddies that had depended on rain said tin of the 
research institute 
he said that allowed two good crops a year instead of one and 
with the addition of fertilizer the farms switched to highyield 
varieties that produce two or three times as much grain 
to boost production further he said the government must 
increase support to farmers and attract foreign investment in 
agriculture 
an immediate problem is a fertilizer shortage that western 
businessmen said was hurting production 
the soviet union has supplied 90 percent of vietnams needs 
under a barter contract that expires this year but says future 
economic deals must be based on commercial merit not the 
fraternal socialism of the past 
frictions could increase in the global rice trade vietnam 
whose major customers include china india and african countries 
has penetrated traditional thai markets with prices 30 to 40 a 
ton lower than thailands after thailand complained the 
vietnamese agreed to raise their prices 
