<TEXT>
three centuries on the battle 
of the boyne still counts as a current event in northern ireland 
every 12th of july finds hundreds of flute and drum bands out on 
the streets of villages and towns rattling windows with thunderous 
lambeg drums and tootling stirring ditties that cast the battle of 
the boyne as a protestant triumph over a roman catholic despot 
stern men in dark suits and bowler hats black umbrellas tightly 
furled march in the orange sashes of the loyal orange institution 
banners salute king william iii king billy the victor at the 
river boyne 
your fourth of july your declaration of independence is seen 
by americans as the point in history where they secured their 
freedom secured their liberty as individuals from an oppressive 
tyrannical power said ronnie hanna general manager of the 
ulster society we would see 12th of july in similar terms 
if you were an englishman you might say this is a kind of 
bizarre continuation of a religious controversy said atq 
stewart a professor of history at queens university in belfast 
in fact stewart said it is about a problem that exists now 
that problem which underlies 21 years of violence and nearly 
2800 deaths is a population divided between 1 million protestants 
loyal to british rule and 600000 roman catholics who identify with 
ireland 
the parades combine history and current events as they have 
every year since 1985 orangemen will reaffirm their opposition to 
the angloirish agreement which gave the irish government a say in 
the provinces affairs 
the 12th is a public holiday in northern ireland but not a 
mandatory one it is a protestant holiday honoring a protestant 
king 
the sash my father wore one of the most popular of the 
orange marching songs says the winners at the boyne fought to 
maintain our unity religion laws and freedom 
an exhibition at the ulster museum however stresses that the 
battle was an episode in a larger european struggle against king 
louis xiv of france 
none of the kings in conflict cared particularly about ireland 
and the irish says a panel at the exhibit james came to 
ireland solely to recover his english throne william solely to 
defeat james 
james ii a convert to roman catholicism was removed from the 
english throne in the glorious revolution of 1688 his daughter 
mary and soninlaw william of orange were invited to rule 
with backing from louis xiv james tried to make a comeback 
through ireland 
on july 1 july 12 on the modern calendar william commanded 
dutchmen danes french huguenots english germans and northern 
irish protestants the forces james led were from france germany 
england and ireland 
james made his stand at the boyne the last physical obstacle 
between williams army and dublin william had superior numbers and 
proved to be the superior tactician 
inevitably it was all far more complicated than the 
traditional symbols even to the point that there were people from 
the same families on different sides said william maguire 
curator of the ulster museum exhibition 
indeed pope innocent xi sided not with the catholic louis but 
with king william the protestant kings men wore sprigs of green 
a color now always identified with ireland and opposed to the 
orange 
what often strikes me as a historian is that everybody knows 
today that whats happening is immensely complicated and everyday 
life is immensely complicated and yet you are somehow expecting a 
simple version of the past and are content with it as if the past 
never was real life maguire said 
james fled ireland after the battle although his forces were 
not finally defeated until the battle at aughrim in western ireland 
in 1691 
the irish attached a rude name to james called him james the 
s maguire said thats his popular irish title and james 
went off blaming the irish for letting him down quite unjustly 
the orangemen with their banners showing king billy astride a 
pawing white horse often have cast the battle on religious lines 
the old marching song protestant boys recalls when james 
half a bigot and more of a knave with masses and frenchmen the 
land would enslave 
catholic nationalists and protestant unionists agree on what 
william represents in the 1920s irish rebels attacked the statue 
of william in dublin even to the extent of trucking it to a 
junkyard and lopping off its head 
the boyne valley is in ireland halfway between dublin and the 
border with northern ireland the orange orders hopes for a big 
300th anniversary ceremony on the battlefield were dropped because 
of strenuous opposition 
although the songs sometimes give the impression the orange 
order fought at the boyne it was founded in 1795 after a skirmish 
between protestants and catholics in county armagh 
in his book the narrow ground stewart notes that orange 
parades were blamed for half a dozen riots in belfast between 1813 
and 1914 
it was a protestant parade that led to street battles in 
londonderry in 1969 that drew the british army into northern 
ireland and revived the irish republican armys armed campaign 
against british rule 
the provocation alleged by catholics may arise simply from the 
fact that orangeism is a symbol of something intensely hated or 
from the display of party colors and playing of party tunes or 
from that most menacing of sounds even to protestant ears the 
thunder of orange drums stewart wrote 
for unionists history is a 17th century drama of peril 
resistance and triumph the threat came in 1641 when the irish 
rebelled and murdered protestant colonists resistance in 1688 
when the apprentice boys slammed the gates of derry against james 
victory in 1690 
you have to remember that 1641 was within living memory for 
most people in the 1690s hanna said this is why people rushed 
to londonderry in 1688 1689 because they thought it was a rerun 
of 1641 
it has often been said that we have a siege mentality said 
george patton executive officer of the orange orders grand lodge 
in belfast 
im not sure whether its a mental state or an actual thing 
weve been under attack almost continuously were still under 
siege to a degree today its the ira murdering our people 
patton said the three orange lodges will be out marching early 
in his village of scarva population 400 then travel to tandragee 
for the district parade with 18 other lodges then join a 
countywide parade 
on the 13th scarva is overrun with 50000 people or more for 
the annual sham fight a halfhour battle of the boyne with 
wooden swords 
the orange order has about 100000 members including most of 
northern irelands leading protestant politicians and is a potent 
force in the province 
its due to the orange order largely that the battle of the 
boyne has been singled as being the crucial thing maguire said 
the battle of aughrim was a far greater battle far more 
decisive far more bloody but of course from a public relations 
point of view it was far less interesting there were no kings 
there 
