<TEXT>
the pamphlet had been buried in a time 
capsule for more than a century its authors long dead and by the 
time it reached sherelyn ogden the words within had been lost to 
the ravages of acid and time 
i unwrapped it and it was a little heap of crumbs just a 
heap of crumbs she said there was just no way of telling what 
anything was 
ogden is a document preservationist but this pamphlet printed 
on the acidic paper that came into vogue after the industrial 
revolution was beyond preservation it was a casualty of the war 
being waged to halt the disintegration of our nations history 
before it all turns to dust 
its very urgent said merrily smith a preservationist at 
the library of congress almost all of the books that were 
produced after 1850 had a lot of acid in them theres huge numbers 
of brittle material 
and if the movement towards embrittlement cant be stopped 
then were looking at a tremendous loss of scholarship she said 
the problem dates to the middle of the 18th century when demand 
for paper exploded manufacturers abandoned the traditional cotton 
and linen rags from which they made paper for cheaper more 
available wood pulp 
to keep ink from spreading over this lowquality paper the 
manufacturers added aluminum sulphate and alumrosin chemicals 
that cause paper to become increasingly acidic and brittle over 
time 
while europe also is affected the situation is considered 
critical in the united states due to the relative youth of the 
nations paper record 
today an estimated 77 million books in american research 
libraries are dying the new york public library has said 70 
percent of the books printed in this century will be unusable by 
the year 2000 
some 325 million volumes in the library of congress alone are 
considered too brittle to be subjected to normal handling smith 
said 
staff members at the northeast document conservation center the 
nations largest are working to preserve some of the best of 
americas past in addition to classic volumes of writing the 
center has rescued original drawings by frank lloyd wright 
benedict arnolds oath of loyalty to the united states and john f 
kennedys fourthgrade report card 
the pace at the northeast center in andover does not seem 
frantic staff members sit on high stools under warm and bright 
lights their heads bent as they touch cracked and stained pages 
some wearing white aprons poke at paper floating in the large 
shallow baths that take up much of the room 
on a recent day the book bindery was still but for the small 
gestures of a single staff member peering at shreds of paper some 
no bigger than a fingernail strewn about a large easel 
ann russell the centers executive director agrees that the 
task of stalling the erosion of millions of books is no less than 
an emergency every day is another book too brittle to be read an 
ineradicable stain on an ansel adams original print a piece of 
history gone 
some of the kinds of materials we work on like nitrate 
photographic negatives some of our clients are monitoring their 
collections and every month they can say how many more of them have 
faded russell said theyre just watching their images 
disappear 
the cost of the conservation war will be dear in part because 
of its laborintensive nature 
at the center workers peel away damaging adhesives remove the 
books from their bindings and wash paper in a buffer solution they 
add new backings of japanese paper which is strong translucent 
and acidfree they touch up photographs and rebind books in 
leather with tones painstakingly matched to the original they keep 
a written record of all that they do 
in one case the patient was a huge map of europe used in the 
field by general john j pershing in world war i with 1200 tiny 
pins to mark troop movements and color codes signifying each units 
strength 
staff members picked off the pins recorded their locations and 
the colors underneath treated the map and returned each pin to its 
spot the project commissioned by the west point museum took two 
months 
the committee for preservation and access reported a typical 
large university research library would spend 240 million over 20 
years to maintain and microfilm its holdings books can sometimes 
cost 1000 and up to salvage said ogden 
the massachusetts town of marblehead paid 150000 for the 
center to preserve handpainted wallpaper hanging in a historic 
mansion 
in addition to having their collections restored book by book 
institutions also may use mass deacidification processes which 
employ chemical solvents and do not involve taking apart the book 
these methods are much cheaper averaging between 5 and 10 a 
volume smith said 
libraries also are putting parts of their collections on 
microfilm which can cost about 50 per volume smith said 
a concerted effort to identify the nations most complete 
collections and microfilm them is under way led by the national 
endowment for the humanities russell said 
hope for the future however experts agree lies not only in a 
mad scramble to hold on to whats been written todays books must 
be printed on acidfree or alkaline paper preservationists say 
paper manufacturers are beginning to listen russell said 
its finally starting to happen at this point theyve really 
heard the message she said every major manufacturer has at 
least one alkaline mill and now they have some stake in promoting 
this as a product 
the change comes none too soon the advance of brittle books is 
outpacing the preservationists they say 
in the library of congress which spends millions on 
preservation workers transfer between 11000 and 13000 volumes on 
microfilm per year smith said meanwhile about 70000 of the 
librarys volumes move into brittle status annually she said 
its not for lack of interest or for lack of money she 
said its just that theres lots of money to be spent on this i 
would say its a race against time and were losing 
</TEXT>
