private citizens frustrated by the pace of 
prosecution in the 325 billion savings and loan mess could 
themselves sue alleged defrauders and pocket damages under a plan 
sponsors want to add to the senates omnibus crime bill 
the socalled bounty hunter plan is drawing fire from the 
justice department which says it might end up snarling criminal 
investigations already under way 
but sponsors say it could prove to be precisely what is needed 
to prod the cleanup into high gear 
the united states has just experienced the greatest financial 
theft in our history carried out by thousands of people and the 
wheels of justice grind with agonizing slowness said sen paul 
simon dill 
the general accounting office estimates that the savings and 
loan bailout will cost taxpayers between 325 and 500 billion 
depending on inflation interest rates and other economic 
conditions 
the bounty hunter plan is the last unresolved point in the 
wideranging crime package which is set for a vote on wednesday 
chief provisions of the package call for curbs on nine 
semiautomatic assault weapons plus capital punishment for 30 
federal crimes ranging from presidential assassination to espionage 
some senate liberals are disgruntled about the death penalty 
provisions and conservatives are ill at ease with any restrictions 
on the right to bear arms 
always anxious to show crimefighting zeal in an election year 
though senators are expected to whisk the package through without 
difficulty once the savings and loan dispute is wrapped up 
the bill then goes to the house where the judiciary committee 
already is at work on a distinctively different anticrime 
blueprint 
the bounty hunter plan is cosponsored by simon and sen 
william v roth jr rdel sen john heinz rpa has urged 
something similar 
endorsed by consumer advocate ralph nader the plan would cover 
savings and loan fraud under the false claims act which allows 
individuals to file fraud suits and pocket a portion of the damages 
as a reward 
of course those filing suit would have to have inside knowledge 
of specific savings and loan fraud and before setting off on their 
own they would first have to give federal prosecutors a chance to 
act on the problem 
critics at the justice department however say the false claims 
act is unconstitutional and ought to be junked 
the department prevailed on senators two weeks ago to postpone 
action on the plan it argued that federal agents on the trail of 
sampl swindlers were liable to get sidetracked into endless reviews 
of individual claims under the measure 
it also said the plan might spawn a quagmire of conflicting 
court cases and ultimately torpedo efforts to put sampl crooks behind 
bars 
by postponing action on the proposal the senate gave sponsors 
additional time for their sales pitch 
theres a game plan however in case talks fizzle if that 
happens lawmakers intend to go ahead and vote on the crime package 
and bring the savings and loan provisions to the floor later as a 
separate bill 
the senate already has done the hard work on the crime bill 
