negotiators plan to meet with white house counterparts in search of 
an agreement to cut the federal budget deficit by 50 billion in 
the fiscal year starting oct 1 
agreement has been elusive after nearly two months of talks but 
the bargaining intensified after president bush eased his position 
against taxes on june 26 saying he now believes they must be 
included in any budget pact 
participants say they hope a package of higher taxes and 
spending cuts can be agreed to before congress leaves for its 
august recess 
the senate armed services committee has scheduled closed 
sessions much of the week to craft a defense authorization bill for 
the next fiscal year 
controversial issues on the agenda include the bush 
administrations planned purchase of 75 b2 stealth bombers at more 
than 815 million each spending on the strategic defense 
initiative and the fate of the v22 osprey tiltrotor aircraft 
complicating the issue is uncertainty over the size of the total 
budget president bush has proposed 307 billion in military 
spending but lawmakers have balked at that amount 
sen sam nunn dga chairman of the armed services panel has 
said that the committee will fashion two bills one to his budget 
range of 289 billion to 291 billion and another to the senate 
budget committee total of 286 billion 
