<TEXT>
a new test can detect downs syndrome in fetuses 
in one day rather than the standard three weeks a company says 
the procedure should not replace standard testing yet but in 
the future it may provide faster and cheaper results for expectant 
couples said stephen turner of oncor inc 
the company based in gaithersburg md said its testing system 
can detect abnormal numbers of certain chromosomes in fetal cells 
that are extracted from the womb using standard procedures 
downs syndrome is a form of mental retardation caused by having 
three copies rather than two of chromosome no 21 it occurs in 
about one in every 800 births 
oncor said its testing system can also detect diseasecausing 
abnormal numbers of copies of chromosomes 13 18 x and y but it 
cannot detect other chromosomal abnormalities or defects in 
specific genes turner said 
oncor which develops genetic tests started selling the downs 
syndrome portion of the system in june 
traditional chromosome testing takes about three weeks because 
once cells are extracted from the womb they must be grown in the 
laboratory and treated before their chd chromosome analysis it can indicate 
highrisk samples for 
priority testing and confirm cases that were difficult to diagnose 
turner said 
in the future he said he believes the test will be used by 
itself to allow a oneday answer to people and eliminate the 
anxiety they have now in waiting three weeks it should also cut 
the cost of testing he said 
dr charles epstein chairman of the national down syndrome 
societys science advisory board said the new test could be useful 
if further research shows it to be accurate 
people who seek chromosome testing are under tremendous 
emotional stress and would like to get the answers more quickly 
he said 
aubrey milunsky of the boston university school of medicine said 
he believes the tests accuracy will prove acceptable and that it 
could promote chromosome testing for women younger than 35 
insurance companies generally will not pay for testing in such 
women because they run less risk of chromosomal abnormalities than 
older women do most laboratories charge 600 to 800 for the 
standard analysis milunsky said 
the new test should be far less expensive so more younger women 
could afford it he said insurance companies might eventually 
cover it he said 
if a test result is negative a woman could be assured with a 
high degree of certainty that her fetus is free of the 
abnormalities the test seeks he said a positive result should be 
confirmed by standard analysis he said 
