<TEXT>
people increase their risk of colon and 
rectal cancer when they eat a lot of saturated fat and dont 
exercise according to a study of chinese residents of north 
america and china 
this is a message everyone needs to hear not just the 
chinese said stanford university epidemiologist alice s 
whittemore chief author of the study the findings are to be 
published in the journal of the national cancer institute this 
month 
we began the project because we noticed that the rate of 
colorectal cancer is four to five times higher among 
chineseamericans than among chinese in china said anna 
wuwilliams a coauthor at the university of southern california 
she said the rate of colorectal cancer among chinese men in los 
angeles county and san francisco was close to rate of white men in 
those areas so the researchers set out to find out what changed 
after the move to the united states 
wuwilliams said the study found about a fivefold increase in 
risk of colorectal cancer associated with a sedentary lifestyle and 
a diet with more than 20 grams about twothirds of an ounce of 
saturated fat a day for men in north america 
the risk of colorectal cancer is increased only about 20 percent 
among sedentary people who eat a lowfat diet she added 
the university said the researchers interviewed 905 colorectal 
cancer patients and 2488 healthy people all were chinese about 
half of each group lived in china and half in north america the 
researchers compared patterns of diet and activity 
after lung cancer colorectal cancer is the second leading cause 
of cancer death in the united states with an estimated 110000 new 
cases of colon cancer and 45000 new cases of rectal cancer this 
year according to the american cancer society the group said 
annual us deaths total 60900 from colon cancer and 7600 from 
rectum cancer 
the cancer group said previously identified factors that raise 
the risk of colorectal cancer include inflammatory bowel disease 
and a personal or family history of cancer or polyps in the colon 
or rectum it listed a highfat lowfiber diet as a suspected risk 
factor 
