<TEXT>
improve your personal finances by paying higher 
taxes 
outlandish as it may sound thats the idea bandied about by 
many financial analysts these days so far sophisticated investors 
on wall street seem to be buying it 
of course only a short time has passed since president bushs 
reversal late last month of his long and outspoken stand against 
tax increases 
assuming that he and congress now will agree on a plan aimed at 
raising revenues of the federal government it remains to be seen 
what specific form the tax measures might take 
still people in the investment world long noted for 
freemarket preferences and distaste of anything that smacks of 
bigger government have so far behaved as though they are pleased 
to see what has happened 
indeed the news was greeted by a rise in both stock and bond 
prices as interest rates fell 
that reaction goes against a lot of traditional thinking about 
economics and finance 
how well would an economy already struggling with tight credit 
conditions and weak consumer spending bear the added burden of a 
tax increase what havoc might a recession wreak on the investment 
markets at a time when the stock market has only recently hit 
record highs 
most economists concede that those are legitimate and worrisome 
questions for the moment however they say investors seem to be 
betting that such perils will be averted 
the optimistic case rests on two main expectations that a tax 
increase would help break a persistent logjam in washington and 
reduce the federal budget deficit and that interest rates would 
drop as a result probably with a push from the federal reserve 
from that individuals and family money managers might reap such 
prospective benefits as lower mortgage rates and support for the 
slumping real estate market bond prices would rise taking with 
them the net asset values of the publics large holdings of income 
mutual funds 
progress on the deficit furthermore would bring relief on what 
john connolly an analyst at the wall street firm of dean witter 
reynolds inc calls the no 1 economic problem of the united 
states the failure of domestic savings to satisfy our investment 
needs 
dependence on foreign capital to fill the gap has helped drive 
us interest rates to persistently high levels in comparison with 
the inflation rate connolly says 
the governments borrowing to cover its deficit has diverted 
capital that could be contributing to prosperity and growth in the 
private economy 
much of this argument is general and theoretical it provides no 
specifics on how savers and investors can make their paychecks and 
savings stretch further 
some also might protest that lower interest rates could actually 
cause savers more pain than gain in the short run by reducing the 
dollar returns available on investments like moneymarket mutual 
funds and bank certificates of deposit 
but anything that provides longterm influences for lower 
interest rates and higher stock prices would logically stand to 
help the budgets of a great many households 
eventually a more prosperous economy and a government on 
sounder financial footing might put pressure on politicians to 
lower taxes once again 
that at least is the kind of reasoning that has governed the 
response of large investors so far 
if their optimism should falter it stands to reason that they 
will serve notice of their change of heart in the financial 
marketplace the announcement would come in the form of a drop 
in the stock market and a rise in interest rates 
