<TEXT>
author peter jenkins likes to tell the 
story about how he walked across the country and picked middle 
tennessee for his home 
then came the day he heard general motors corp had decided to 
build its biggest automobile plant a mile from his 150acre farm 
neither he nor many tennesseans are sure the impact from the 
investment which is costing gm at least 3 billion is totally 
welcome in the rolling hills and horse country now facing 
pressures ranging from overcrowded schools to new sources of 
pollution 
i look out my window at night and i see this red glow they 
keep the lights on there jenkins said in an interview 
gms saturn corp plant nearly complete is expected to begin 
sending cars to dealers nationwide any week now but life in tiny 
spring hill has long since changed 
the solitude of spring hill population 1094 was shattered 
first by news media publicizing the bucolic charm of the area one 
of several gm was considering as the home for what it hoped would 
be the car of the future 
then came the speculators who drove up the price of real estate 
after gms july 30 1985 announcement that it had determined 
spring hill was the ideal location 
the companys first new nameplate since 1917 the compact will 
compete primarily with the honda civic and toyota corolla and cost 
10000 to 12000 will be built here by a combination of 
tennesseans and transplants from other gm factories many of whom 
were laid off in earlier costcutting drives 
for many tennesseeans there is irony in gms migration to their 
state decades ago during the depression and warboom years the 
migration mainly went the other way as tennesseeans moved north 
seeking jobs in detroit 
tennessee politicians were elated when gm announced it would 
build a plant and hire 6000 employees to produce a car line called 
saturn that number has since been halved but the financial impact 
on the local economy has nonetheless been farreaching 
for example in maury county where the plant is based 200 
million has been spent for goods services salaries and taxes gm 
provided 125 million for a new spring hill city hall 
at the same time the impact of such a major new employer has 
strained government services especially public education maury 
county school officials are building a new elementary school and 
need about 30 new teachers to deal with 800 additional students 
an 8 percent increase in 1991 enrollment 
the new elementary school we believe should relieve 
overcrowding in the elementary grades maury county school 
superintendent jerry battles said however we expect a 
continuing enrollment pressure at our middle school and high 
school 
in addition the influx of nontennesseeans has created greater 
pressure to accomodate people from diverse cultural and ethnic 
backgrounds which center largely along the differences between 
southerners and northerners 
a lot of the automotive plants up north are in the downtown 
area so those people may be urbanites and accustomed to a faster 
pace of life than the people who live in the smaller towns in 
middle tennessee said dan cornfield a sociology professor at 
vanderbilt university 
there seems to be schisms between northerners whove moved 
down and southerners whove lived here they dont always share the 
same lifestyles so you may get a segregation of people not in 
terms of race 
almost half of the transplanted saturn workers have settled in 
maury county which includes spring hill and columbia the county 
seat the maury county chamber of commerce has estimated 
about a third moved north of spring hill in williamson county 
an affluent bedroom community next to nashville 
for transplants and natives alike the biggest drawback to gms 
arrival has been housing prices which have multiplied and made it 
difficult for many families to find affordable places to live 
the cost of land came back down from the high but its still 
higher than it was on announcement day said bill chaffin an 
official of the maury county chamber of commerce 
we have crowded streets that fall under the heading of i 
guess youd say a problem weve had a lot of interesting new 
people move in which is not a problem weve had our anxieties of 
growth 
that kind of anxiety is the last thing author jenkins expected 
when hed finished walk across america 
i think that for those of us who live in middle tennessee 
not just spring hill when you have a corporation as strong and as 
mighty as general motors we have to make sure we protect the 
lifestyle we love the pace of life and the quality of southern 
lifestyle which i chose over any other lifestyle 
we need to be vigilant and people tend to lose that sense of 
vigilance before its too late he said 
end adv for monday july 9 
