<TEXT>
joel vazquez never thought independence in 
namibia would make any difference to his life as an oceanroving 
commercial spanish fisherman he soon found himself beached like a 
trawler at low tide 
when the new southern african nation was established in april 
it ordered the spanish fleet one of the western worlds largest 
to vacate the rich waters off the namibian coast the move idled 
vazquezs ur elza and 34 other trawlers along with 1500 crew 
members 
a fisherman with a true calling for the sea doesnt know what 
to do when he faces life on land said vazquez 36 the fishing 
crisis could spell an end to his 13 years at sea 
the ships forced from namibia are part of the 175vessel 
deepsea fleet that forms the heart of the spanish fishing 
industry it directly employs 5000 people and indirectly employs 
an additional 45000 canners marketers shipbuilders and suppliers 
ninety percent of the fleet is based in the jagged estuary of 
vigo of northeast spain the most important fishing port of the 
12nation european community 
industry officials say much more of the fleet will be forced to 
drop anchor indefinitely because other countries besides namibia 
have moved to evict foreign fleets from heavily fished breeding 
grounds 
argentina began shutting out spanish trawlers last year and the 
united states and canada banned them from territorial waters in the 
early 1980s morocco has restricted foreign fishing off the saharan 
banks and britain is limiting access to waters off the falkland 
islands in the south atlantic 
spains commercial fishermen partly blame prime minister felipe 
gonzalez for failing to challenge the increased protectionism the 
government says thats part of the price for spains membership in 
the ec which has given it less control over guarding the overseas 
interests of many spanish businesses 
the result has been a growing economic depression for 
vigobased ship owners and all related sectors said gloria sio 
editor of the industry magazine industrias pesqueras 
sio said the presence of the idled ships in vigo harbor 
underscores what she called the administrations failure to control 
public financing for new ships while fishing grounds kept 
diminishing 
right now there are at least 40 ships too many for the places 
available to fish sio said 
statistics compiled by the ministry of agricultures fishing 
division show how the industry has become less productive and the 
country more reliant on imports 
in 1987 for example the deepsea fleets catch totaled nearly 
635000 tons vs about 553000 tons last year frozenfish imports 
have nearly tripled since 1984 to roughly 28000 tons while 
exports have declined by more than 28 percent to roughly 25000 
tons 
for now the ministry has approved a plan to pay idled fisherman 
their average monthly wage of about 600 with a stipend to cover 
social security payments 
the namibian government says part of the reason for the eviction 
order to the spanish ships was to assess the productivity of 
domestic breeding grounds that produce hake an important food fish 
but the namibians have said a study will take at least four 
months and they wont open negotiations on a new accord with the 
spanish until afterward 
our future is totally uncertain said jose fuertes managing 
director of spains hake fishing ship owners assocation 
the administration has had plenty of time to see namibian 
independence coming and to reach a bilateral accord to permit 
spanish fishing but it was just incompetent he said 
unions and shipowners are outraged that spain and the ec are not 
fiercely defending the spanish fleets right to fish overseas 
on may 31 5000 people marched through vigo as the citizens 
movement to save the fleet with backing by politicians 
fishermens unions shipowners associations and chambers of 
commerce gonzalezs socialist party and the socialist general 
workers union were absent 
serafin sa spokesman for the communist fishermans union 
claimed ec fishing commissioner manuel marin a spanish socialist 
has been inept in defending the interests of spanish fishermen 
against those of lowcost fishing nations such as the soviet union 
romania and poland and in foreign fishing banks especially those 
off canada 
the great irony is that while spanish ships are being forced 
out of foreign hake and cod banks from canada to argentina these 
countries are using basically protectionist measures in turn to 
dominate our own ec markets he said 
