<DOCNO> AP900705-0221 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
it looks like something that should be 
piloted by little green men from mars but sikorsky aircrafts 
newest flying machine doesnt need anyone in the cockpit 
extraterrestrial or otherwise 
after four years of secret research the helicopter pioneer has 
unveiled the cypher its entry in the race to develop a pilotless 
aircraft 
the cypher looks like two large ceiling fans bolted together to 
form the spokes of a fiberglass doughnut its 5 feet in diameter 
and weighs about 300 pounds light enough to be carried by two 
people 
a mockup sits inside a storage building at sikorskys 
headquarters in stratford conn awaiting wind tunnel tests 
sikorsky a division of united technologies corp wont start 
production until it receives orders for the cypher 
but company executives predict the aircraft known in the 
industry as an unmanned aerial vehicle or uav will be a big hit 
with military and civilian customers for reconnaissance missions 
searchandrescues flyovers of forest fires and surveillance of 
illicit drug operations 
you can just use your imagination and think about mount st 
helens or chernobyl anywhere you want to get in without risking 
life said william tuttle a sikorsky spokesman 
the american military has used remotecontrol airplanes for 
years mostly as decoys to draw enemy fire away from planes with 
pilots aboard but pentagon strategists have decided they need a 
more versatile helicopterlike aircraft that can take off and land 
vertically and maneuver in inaccessible areas 
if custer had one of these uavs he might have won at little 
big horn said ray coleman of the pentagons joint office for 
unmanned aerial vehicles 
the office was established in 1988 to look at the most promising 
vehicles it invested a modest 160000 in research on the cypher 
last year although congress has prohibited the office from 
spending money on actual production 
work on the cypher began in 1986 when sikorsky was awarded an 
eightmonth study contract by the pentagons defense advanced 
research projects agency the company refused to discuss the actual 
cost of cypher because of the intense competition for government 
contracts 
the cypher uses technology developed by sikorsky nearly two 
decades ago for its xh59a helicopter which used a coaxial rotor 
or double rotary blade to operate 
the double blades rotate in opposite directions giving the 
craft greater stability especially on takeoffs and landings the 
blades rotate within a fiberglass tube where the cyphers fuel and 
payload are stored 
the cypher is controlled by a computer programmed before 
takeoff but its flight pattern can be altered after takeoff if 
necessary said james cycon sikorskys chief engineer for the 
cypher project 
sikorsky engineers say theyre particularly proud of containing 
the blades within a tube because the innovation makes the cypher 
safer for people on the ground during takeoffs or landings the 
blades of competitors under development are exposed like a 
helicopters 
cycon said the cypher is designed to hover 800010000 feet in 
the air for about four hours it can carry a 150pound payload 
such as a surveillance camera 
the cypher can be launched vertically from a small area like 
the deck of a patrol boat sikorsky also is studying the 
possibility of launching cypher from black hawk helicopters which 
it makes for the army 
sikorsky first flew a radiocontrolled 5footdiameter version 
of the cypher in the summer of 1988 in west palm beach fla to 
prove it could actually fly using the coaxial rotor technology 
cycon said 
that vehicle has since been retired and is on display at 
sikorsky headquarters 
during the design work for cypher cycon kept a sign on his wall 
that said time to make the doughnuts and says his children 
are still kidded about having a father who makes flying saucers 
cyphers success would allow sikorsky to expand into new markets 
in the face of defense cuts the company has already been forced to 
lay off about 300 of its 12000 workers because of lower military 
demand 
but sikorsky faces stiff competition in the field of pilotless 
flight a number of domestic and foreign companies are vying for 
defense contracts and are further along in developing their 
products coleman said 
the pentagon already has a contract with canadair to conduct a 
sixmonth test of that firms cl227 or peanut he said the 
british company ml aviation has developed a pilotless vehicle 
called the sprite which resembles a flying barbecue grill 
the unmanned air vehicle market is expected to grow 
dramatically in the next 10 years said mark bobbi of forecast 
international an independent market research firm specializing in 
aerospace and defense but i dont think the cypher will help 
sikorsky much in the next five years 
sikorsky recently submitted information about the cypher to the 
army in hopes the army will decide to order some vehicles so 
production can begin 
larry dickerson another forecast international analyst who is 
watching the uav industry said sikorskys success will depend on 
how it markets the cypher 
its very new and looks different but the military is pretty 
conservativeminded about new and different things he said 
</TEXT>
