helpwanted advertising registered a lackluster 
performance in may indicating a cautious attitude among many 
employers around the nation the conference board reported friday 
the seasonally adjusted helpwanted advertising index compiled 
from a survey of ad volume in 51 newspapers across the country 
registered 137 in may down 2 points from april and 15 points below 
the yearago level the board said 
the word cautious best describes the labor market right 
now said conference board economist ken goldstein there is a 
definite softness in demand consumers government and some 
elements of business investment appear quite sluggish 
most regions of the country particularly new england and the 
middle atlantic states registered declines in helpwanted ads 
and goldstein noted that the drops show no sign of ending soon 
but many southern states as well as parts of texas and oklahoma 
registered gains 
goldstein said exportdriven economic growth is expected to 
boost labor markets in the west later this year and then sweep 
eastward 
ad volume has proven to be sensitive to labor market conditions 
and helps gauge changes in the local regional and national supply 
of jobs 
