<DOCNO> AP900705-0230 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the largest telemarketing fraud ever 
uncovered by visa and mastercard recruited small businesses to 
launder credit card charges the companies contend in a 
multimilliondollar lawsuit unsealed thursday 
federal criminal investigations also are under way in the case 
described as a chain of operations conducting business nationwide 
from bases in florida texas arizona california and other states 
the suit says the scam began with postcards telling consumers 
they had won free cars watches or 5000 prizes when they phoned 
they reached boiler rooms and were pressured to buy water 
purifiers security systems travel packages and vitamins it says 
the defendants claimed that winners identities were verified 
through their credit card numbers the defendants also implied that 
visa and mastercard sponsored the giveaways the suit says 
the suit also alleges the telemarketers misrepresented goods 
failed to deliver them and sent multiple bills for the same product 
defendants scheme undermines a cornerstone of the charge card 
system that member financial institutions be able to evaluate the 
honesty integrity and credit worthiness of those from whom they 
accept charge card deposits visa and mastercard said in the suit 
in los angeles federal court 
the suit seeks unspecified millions of dollars in actual damages 
and 10 million in punitive damages alleging racketeering fraud 
trademark infringement and interfering with contractual 
relationships 
its the largest single telemarketing operation that visa and 
mastercard ever came across said visa spokesman david brancoli 
he estimated such schemes cost the companies up to 200 million 
per year federal trade commission officials believe consumers have 
lost 1 billion a year to telemarketing fraud for the past five 
years 
a central aim of the suit is to stop boiler room operators from 
using third parties to process sales drafts banks usually wont 
set up visa and mastercard accounts for telephone sales operations 
because too many customers refuse to pay leaving the banks holding 
the bag the suit says 
the suit alleges that some defendants were brokers who 
advertised in newspapers like the los angeles times for businesses 
to launder sales drafts for a fee typically 6 percent of sales 
counting broker fees telemarketers may pay 20 percent or more 
of the gross sales to have their drafts deposited said daniel h 
bookin a san francisco attorney for visa and mastercard 
that compares to 2 percent to 3 percent at legitimate businesses 
with merchant accounts at banks 
if these guys couldnt launder theyd be out of business 
bookin said 
visa and mastercard persuaded us district judge edward 
rafeedie last week to issue a temporary restraining order barring 
the telemarketers from using third parties to process credit card 
drafts a hearing on a permanent injunction is set for july 16 
the postal service and the secret service are conducting 
criminal probes according to the suit and one of the defendants 
lorraine g doty 
this thing is much bigger than what is laid out in this 
lawsuit ms doty said in a telephone interview from florida 
ms doty said she and another defendant lillian whitman had 
shut down their boiler room operation in clearwater fla after 
learning that using third parties to process sales drafts violated 
credit card agreements with banks she declined further comment 
saying she hadnt talked to a lawyer 
a central defendant is donald gaines of clearwater who the 
complaint accuses of running boiler rooms and through a phoenix 
business acting as a broker for small businesses willing to 
launder charges 
reached at another business in overland kan gaines declined 
comment saying he had not seen the lawsuit 
altogether the suit names 10 individuals and 11 companies as 
defendants 
we have documented 4 million in losses but were sure the 
total is far larger bookin said 
processing of thirdparty sales drafts is outlawed in only three 
states california florida and wisconsin there is no federal law 
against it although abuses can be prosecuted under other federal 
statutes such as mail fraud and wire fraud 
mastercard and visa have joint programs to warn businesses that 
laundering is banned by their agreements with banks and to detect 
the practice they also are jointly lobbying to have such 
laundering made a federal crime 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

