<TEXT>
federal regulators on thursday ordered 
president bushs son neil to appear at a public hearing to 
explain why as a savings and loan officer he approved loans to a 
business partner 
administrative charges of conflict of interest against the 
presidents son will be taken up at the september hearing 
regulators said 
the loans to business partner bill l walters and purchases of 
property from him totaled more than 100 million according to the 
treasury departments office of thrift supervision 
at the time of the transactions the younger bush was a director 
of silverado banking savings and loan association in denver 
bush in a reply denied that he had violated his duty as a 
director he denied a number of specific charges and said in 
response to others that he lacks sufficient present knowledge or 
information to form a belief as to the allegations 
the administrative charges filed in february and bushs reply a 
month later both were made public for the first time thursday under 
a new thrift office policy the house banking committee released a 
preliminary draft of the charges in june 
an administrative law judge is scheduled to hear the bush case 
sept 25 in denver before making a recommendation to thrift office 
director timothy ryan 
james nesland an attorney for the younger bush said a public 
hearing could be exploited for political purposes but expressed 
confidence that the judge would render a fair opinion 
i think its unfortunate if it creates a political sideshow or 
a media sideshow but im still confident the administrative law 
judge will decide the case on its merits he said 
separately the thrift office announced it was seeking a record 
24 million in restitution and civil penalties from the former 
chairman of columbia savings and loan association of beverly hills 
calif 
the office alleged that thomas spiegel spent millions of the 
thrifts eposits on limousines corporate jets luxury condominiums 
in resort areas trips to europe for himself 7000 in tickets to 
a michael jackson concert and a 55000 gun collection including 
uzi submachine guns 
spiegel a close associate of former drexel burnham junk bond 
chief michael milken built columbia into one of the nations 
largest thrifts and the industrys biggest holder of junk bonds 
with 37 billion at the end of 1989 
columbia is still operating but analysts predict it eventually 
will be seized by the government spiegel stepped down in december 
edward harshfield columbias current chief executive said in a 
statement that the institutions current management cooperated with 
the thrift office and said the allegations do not reflect on 
current management or the institution as a whole 
spiegel meanwhile denied the charges and accused the agency of 
waging a politicallymotivated trial by press release 
bush served on the board of silverado from august 1985 to august 
1988 it collapsed in december 1988 at an estimated cost to 
taxpayers of 1 billion he has denied any wrongdoing 
the charges said bush as a director of silverado voted to 
approve loans totaling 45 million to walters an investor in and 
lender to bushs oil exploration company jnb exploration co he 
also voted to approve silverados purchase of 584 million in 
properties from walters the document said 
the thrift office also said bush inadequately disclosed his ties 
to kenneth good a developer who defaulted on loans to silverado 
ryan will decide after reviewing the administrative hearing on 
the case whether or not to issue a ceaseanddesist order against 
bush prohibiting him from violating regulations in the future 
the agency is not seeking any more serious penalties such as 
financial restitution or banning bush from working for a bank or 
sampl 
from now on the agency generally will release charges and 
conduct hearings in public for the officers of thrifts already 
closed or seized by the government in order to avoid the danger of 
depositor runs proceedings against open sampls generally will 
continue to be conducted in private ryan told a news conference 
the public has a major stake in the cleanup of the thrift 
industry and as a general rule i believe it is reasonable to make 
enforcement proceedings open when dealing with government 
controlled thrifts ryan said 
he said he offered treasury department officials a chance to 
offer advice on the policy but they declined 
the documents on three other unrelated cases also were released 
