<TEXT>
national intergroup inc said thursday it 
would appeal a delaware judges ruling that shareholders must be 
allowed to vote on changes in the companys antitakeover 
provisions 
national intergroup amended its poison pill strategy in january 
diluting the voting power and market value of its shares for 
investors who own more than 10 percent of the company the 
threshold had stood at 20 percent 
vice chancellor maurice hartnett of delawares chancery court on 
tuesday said national intergroup acted improperly and called the 10 
percent limit extremely low 
hartnett said national intergroups board must present the 
changes to the stockholders at its july 25 meeting in pittsburgh 
the ruling is a boost to centaur partners a new york 
partnership that owns 1653 percent of national intergroup and 
walker street another partnership that owns 84 percent of the 
company 
centaur partners which earlier this year tried unsuccessfully 
to gain control of national intergroups board and walker street 
had brought the court action against the company 
national intergroup issued a statement saying they would appeal 
the decision the company said lowering the threshold was a 
necessary and appropriate response to the threat to shareholders 
posed by centaurs acquisition program 
national intergroup formerly the majority owner of national 
steel corp has announced the sale of most of its metals and other 
businesses leaving behind its drug distribution company last 
month national intergroup announced it would change its name to 
foxmeyer corp the name of its drug company and move to dallas 
</TEXT>
