<TEXT>
a federal judge thursday rejected a partial 
verdict in the fraud and racketeering trial of three commodities 
traders and directed the jury to continue their deliberations 
in the ninth day of their deliberations the jurors sent us 
district judge ann c williams a note saying they had reached 
verdicts on some of the counts and were deadlocked on the others 
we feel further deliberations would be unproductive wrote 
benita engledinger the jurys foreman 
after 20 minutes of discussion among lawyers at the judges 
bench williams brought the jurors into the courtroom and told 
them you must continue your deliberations 
the jury was weighing charges against robert m mosky 34 danny 
l scheck 28 and david zatz 43 mosky is a chicago mercantile 
exchange floor broker portrayed by prosecutors as the leader of a 
fraud scheme in the mercs swiss franc futures trading pit 
he is the only defendant charged with racketeering 
the swiss franc traders were the first to stand trial on charges 
stemming from a continuing fbi probe of corruption at the merc and 
the chicago board of trade the worlds biggest commodity markets 
the jury began deliberating june 22 after nearly seven weeks of 
testimony 
moskys lawyer elliott samuels said the prolonged 
deliberations were wearing on the defendants and their lawyers 
its tough its hard on the nerves said samuels 
the defendants were accused of shifting their personal losses 
from trading errors into their customers accounts then hiding 
their practices by changing or destroying trading records 
mosky scheck and zatz were charged last august with more than a 
dozen counts each of mail or wire fraud and violations of the 
commodity exchange act each count carries a maximum penalty of 
five years in prison and a 150000 fine 
if convicted of racketeering conspiracy mosky faces a maximum 
prison term of 20 years he also could be forced to forfeit 
personal assets 
</TEXT>
